    "instruction": "Load trace.csv, parse timestamp with unit='s' and utc=True. Restrict to the candidate services: checkoutservice, currencyservice, emailservice, productcatalogservice, recommendationservice. For each (cmdb_id, trace_name) compute the global p95 using the full available series (do not filter by time yet). Then filter rows to the incident window 2024-01-15 17:27:22 to 2024-01-15 17:57:22 UTC (inclusive). For each pair produce: total_points_in_window, anomaly_count_in_window (value >= p95), earliest_anomaly_timestamp (UTC) if any, and max_relative_violation = max((value - p95)/p95) across anomalies. Return only rows with anomaly_count_in_window>0, sorted by anomaly_count_in_window desc then max_relative_violation desc. Limit output to top 20 rows. Additionally, include up to 5 example trace anomaly rows (timestamp, cmdb_id, trace_name, value) for the top 3 (cmdb_id, trace_name) pairs." }

{
    "analysis": "We observed pervasive 'socket' KPI anomalies across almost all candidate services starting ~2024-01-15 17:30:00 UTC. Trace 'error_rate' series were flagged but appear to be threshold artifacts (global p95 == 0 and values == 0), so they are not reliable indicators. Logs may help identify which service is actually failing (socket-related errors) and whether any service shows elevated error logs. The next step is to inspect log.csv (log.error_count and log.row_count) within the incident window for the candidate services to see if any service emitted error logs or notable log volume changes coincident with the socket anomalies. Since error_logs.csv is empty, focus on aggregated log counts and a few example rows per candidate service.",
