    "instruction": "Load metric.csv and parse timestamp with unit='s' and utc=True. Restrict to candidate services (checkoutservice, currencyservice, emailservice, productcatalogservice, recommendationservice) and to kpi_name == 'socket'. For each cmdb_id first compute the global p95 using the full available series (do not filter by time for p95). Then filter rows to the incident window 2024-01-15 17:27:22 to 2024-01-15 17:57:22 UTC inclusive. For each cmdb_id return these fields: cmdb_id, count_all (full-series count for socket), p95 (global), total_points_in_window, anomaly_count_in_window (points in window with value >= p95), earliest_anomaly_timestamp (UTC, null if none), mean_value_in_window, max_value_in_window, max_relative_violation_in_window where relative violation = max((value - p95)/p95) over anomalies (use absolute ratio; if p95==0 set relative violation to NaN). Sort rows by anomaly_count_in_window desc then max_value_in_window desc. Limit output to all candidate services (max 5 rows). Also return up to 10 example socket rows (timestamp, cmdb_id, kpi_name, value) from the window ordered by timestamp asc." }

{
    "analysis": "We have followed the prescribed workflow so far: preprocessed and computed global thresholds for metrics, detected widespread anomalies in the 'socket' KPI across almost all candidate services beginning ~2024-01-15 17:30:00 UTC, inspected traces (many trace.error_rate series were flagged but that appears to be a threshold artifact because p95==0 and values==0), and checked logs (no log.error_count entries during the window). The metric-level signal strongly indicates a socket-related problem affecting multiple services simultaneously. According to the root-cause localization rules, when multiple service-level faults occur we should use traces (duration/latency or inter-service trace metrics) to identify the most-downstream faulty service in call chains. We have not yet inspected trace duration/latency features to find downstream propagation or which service shows the most significant timing degradations. This is the next necessary step to localize the root-cause service among the candidate services.",
    "completed": "False",
    "instruction": "Load trace.csv and parse timestamp with unit='s' and utc=True. Restrict to candidate services (checkoutservice, currencyservice, emailservice, productcatalogservice, recommendationservice). Identify all trace_name values that contain the substring 'duration' (case-sensitive). For each (cmdb_id, trace_name) compute the global p95 using the full available series (do not filter first). Then filter rows to the incident window 2024-01-15 17:27:22 to 2024-01-15 17:57:22 UTC inclusive. For each pair produce: total_points_in_window, anomaly_count_in_window (value >= p95), earliest_anomaly_timestamp (UTC) if any, and max_relative_violation = max((value - p95)/p95) across anomalies (if p95==0 set relative violation to NaN). Return only rows with anomaly_count_in_window>0 sorted by anomaly_count_in_window desc then max_relative_violation desc. Limit output to top 20 rows. Also include up to 5 example trace rows (timestamp, cmdb_id, trace_name, value) for the top 3 (cmdb_id, trace_name) pairs." }

{
    "analysis": "We found pervasive socket KPI anomalies across almost all candidate services starting ~2024-01-15 17:30:00 UTC. Trace error_rate series were unreliable due to zero p95 thresholds. Crucially, trace duration analysis revealed large, sparse latency spikes centered on currencyservice (notably trace.from_root.duration_p95 and trace.from_root.duration_mean) with very large relative violations (~149x and ~82x) and earliest anomalies at 2024-01-15 17:36:00 UTC; other services show minor or fewer duration anomalies. Logs show no error_count events for candidate services. According to the workflow, the most likely root-cause service is currencyservice (it is the service with the strongest trace-duration degradation and appears in impacted call chains). However, we have not yet confirmed the failure reason/resource (socket vs. network latency vs. CPU/memory/disk). The metric-level socket KPI is abnormal across many services (suggesting socket-related symptoms), but we must inspect currencyservice resource KPIs (cpu, mem, diskio, socket, workload) using global thresholds computed on full series and filtered to the incident window to identify which resource fault best explains the latency spikes around 17:36 and 17:52 UTC.",
    "completed": "False",
    "instruction": "Focus on currencyservice. Load metric.csv and parse timestamp with unit='s' and utc=True. Identify available kpi_name values for currencyservice. For each KPI (only those available for currencyservice) compute the global p95 and p5 using the full series (do not filter first). Then filter rows to the incident window 2024-01-15 17:27:22 to 2024-01-15 17:57:22 UTC inclusive. For each KPI return: kpi_name, count_all (full-series count), p95, p5, total_points_in_window, anomaly_count_in_window (value >= p95 or value <= p5 as appropriate), earliest_anomaly_timestamp (UTC if any), mean_value_in_window, max_value_in_window, max_relative_violation_in_window (for high anomalies use (value-p95)/p95, for low anomalies use (p5-value)/p5; if denominator==0 set NaN). Sort by anomaly_count_in_window desc then max_relative_violation desc. Limit output to all currencyservice KPIs. Additionally, return up to 10 example metric rows (timestamp, cmdb_id, kpi_name, value) for currencyservice from the window ordered by timestamp asc to inspect raw values around 17:36 and 17:52." }

Review: Metric analysis showed pervasive socket anomalies across services beginning ~2024-01-15 17:30:00 UTC; trace analysis revealed very large latency spikes centered on currencyservice (notably at ~17:36 UTC); logs contained no application errors. These signals point to a socket-level failure in currencyservice as the root cause.

